[1
Date: Sun, 21 Mar 1999 14:21:19 -0500
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>

Found this on the wires today. Any information on the economic impact of
this to Malaysia? Is Malaysia a major pig exporter? Will banning the
export of pork impact on possible transmission or have I forgotten basic
epidemiology and entomology. Is JE transmitted in the meat of infected
pigs? (has the _Culex_ suddenly developed a taste for slabs of raw pork
with live virus ingestion from the residual blood in the meat?)
Source:  Xinhua News Agency, 21 Mar 1999

Thailand has imposed an import ban on Malaysian pork in a bid to stop the
spread of pig-born Japanese encephalitis, a statement of the Ministry of
Public Health available Sunday said.
"The livestock department has banned all pork imports and live pigs from
Malaysia and set up an ad-hoc patrol unit along the common border," the
statement said.
Meanwhile, public health experts warned the public not to panic as no cases
of the disease had been detected in Thailand.
Japanese encephalitis, which can cause inflammation of the brain, is spread
to humans from pigs by the _Culex_ mosquito. The disease has been reported
to cause at least 53 deaths in Malaysia.
The Public Health Ministry warned people to avoid mosquitoes and not to
keep live pigs near houses.
Officials manning customs checkpoints on the Thai-Malaysian border had
stepped up vigilance to ensure Malaysian pig-virus epidemic did not spread
to Thailand.
The Malaysian viral outbreak has killed at least 53 people since October,
and troops have begun killing more than 300,000 pigs in a bid to contain
it. Almost all of the 53 victims lived or worked near pig farms.
Neighboring Singapore has also suspended the import of live pigs from
Malaysia and Indonesia.
--
Marjorie P. Pollack
e-mail: pollackmp@mindspring.com
[And not a mention of the Hendra-like virus. - Mod.CHC
