[2
Date: Mon, 22 Mar 1999 10:25:12 +1200
From: Mark Bosson <bossonm@maf.govt.nz>

Perhaps some consideration should be given to possible host species of the
virus - such as bats. A survey of these animals might isolate the offending
organism.
If the Hendra[-like virus is able to be maintained in pigs it should not
be assumed that the routes of transmission will be the same as those found
in horses in Australia. Additionally the infectivity of the organism may
be different - surely serious precautions should be taken in the handling
of potentially infected pigs.
--
Mark Bosson
Disease Investigator
National Centre for Disease Investigfation
Wallaceville, New Zealand
PH: 64 (0)4 526 5600
FAX: 64 (0)4 526 5601
e-mail: bossonm@maf.govt.nz
[Correct on both counts. I expect that the epidemiologic studies to be
done by Ken Lam and the international team of consultants will soon
investigate the flying fox roosts and see what's what there. The
appropriate studies cannot all be done in one day or one week. Still, all
questions are good one and should be addressed seriously. The first
problem to solve is how to stop this epizoodemic.
It is frightening to consider that people recently were beating some of
these pigs to death with boards. Surely someone was splattered with blood,
and that couldn't possibly be a good thing. - Mod.CHC
