[3
Date: Sun, 21 Mar 1999 18:51:47 -0500
From: Greg Folkers <GFOLKERS@niaid.nih.gov>
Source: Star (Malaysia), Sunday, March 21, 1999
<http://www.jaring.my/~star/current/news.html>

Doctors at the University Hospital are experimenting treating patients
suspected of having contracted the Hendra-like virus with a drug called
ribavirin. UH head of Medical Microbiology Department Prof. Lam Sai Kit
said the doctors investigating the Japanese Encephalitis (JE) outbreak
discovered a Hendra-like virus in laboratory specimens taken from the
victims.
"We know it is a Hendra-like virus and we want to determine how important
its role is in JE," Prof. Lam told a press conference when asked whether
the virus they had found was the Hendra virus. He said the drug, which had
long been available, was an effective anti-viral measure against the
respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) which causes bronchitis in children.
[RSV is a member of the family Paramyxoviridae, as is Hendra virus. -
Mod.CHC
"We do not know enough about the virus but we believe the drug would be
effective. Ribavirin inhibits the growth of the RSV and may work for the
Hendra-like virus," he said. The hospital, Prof. Lam said, started
treating patients with the drug from Friday and would only know whether it
worked if the patients' conditions did not deteriorate.
"The seven-day regime treatment with the drug costs about RM3,000 and the
hospital is currently footing the bill," he said. Prof. Lam also said the
potential side-effects of the drug included anaemia, but the recovery of
the patients outweighed the side-effects. He said since the outbreak, 39
victims from the Bukit Pelanduk area had been admitted into the hospital.
Of this, six had since died but seven had been sent home after treatment
proved successful. [etiology unstated - Mod.CHC
He also said Dr Chua Kaw Bing from the UH, who had isolated the Hendra-like
virus, had gone to the United States to confirm the isolated agent and the
result would be known in a few days.
He said experts from Australia and the Centres for Disease Control (CDC) in
the United States would be here next week to help study the virus. The
experts, said Prof. Lam, had also developed a test kit to determine how
common the illness was.
However, he refuted claims that the virus was transmitted from horses,
saying a study in Australia which tested 200 people who handled horses
infected with the virus showed that they did not get infected. [The first
person to die with Hendra virus infection in Queensland had shoved a bolus
of food down the throat of a horse that subsequently died of Hendra virus.
- Mod.CHC
Pork consumption also does not appear to transmit the virus, while
butchers and housewives who handle pork do not get infected, he said [Huh?
- Mod.CHC.
"Culling the pigs is a good way of breaking the chain of transmission.
However, people should continue taking vaccination for JE," he said.
Meanwhile, Deputy Education Minister Datuk Dr Fong Chan Onn said the
ministry was trying its best to help overcome the current crisis. He said
he was grateful that hospital staff were able to identify the new strain of
the virus within a short time. "We will continue to do our best to help the
Health Ministry," he said.
--
Gregory K. Folkers, M.S., M.P.H.
